natural problem: All sides of the convex pentagon $ABCDE$ are of equal length, and $\angle A = \angle B = 90^\circ$.  What is the degree measure of $\angle E$?
natural solution: Because $AB=BC=EA$ and $\angle A = \angle B = 90^\circ$, quadrilateral $ABCE$ is a square, so $\angle AEC = 90^\circ$. [asy] pair A,B,C,D,G; A=(0,10); B=(10,10); C=(10,0); D=(5,-7.1); G=(0,0); draw(A--B--C--D--G--cycle,linewidth(0.8));
draw(G--C); label("$A$",A,W); label("$B$",B,E); label("$C$",C,E); label("$D$",D,S); label("$E$",G,W); [/asy] Also $CD=DE=EC$, so $\triangle CDE$ is equilateral and $\angle CED = 60^\circ$.
